<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JAN 93 / Money Markets: Weaker tone in Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE WAS a much weaker tone to trading in both European cash and futures
yesterday as pressures inside the exchange rate mechanism eased, writes
James Blitz.
Cash rates in the French franc market fell as the currency strengthened
against the D-Mark, moving above FFr3.41 per D-Mark. There was continuing
tension in the Irish punt money market, with the authorities announcing that
overnight rates will be set at 50 per cent from today.
The effects of Tuesday's Franco-German communique supporting the franc
continued to be felt in markets, and there was a little more confidence
about the prospects of the franc surviving the current crisis without the
need to devalue.
Three-month money fell to 12 7/8 per cent from the 14 per cent rate of the
day before, and the overnight rate was down to 12 1/2 per cent from
Tuesday's 15 per cent.
The more positive tone was felt in French franc futures, where the March
contract finished 17 basis points higher at 90.46.
Euromark futures enjoyed a minor rally yesterday following rumours that the
Bundesbank was planning a 50 basis-point cut in the Lombard rate to support
the French franc. The March contract rose 7 basis points to a high of 92.25
on the rumour, but fell back to close unchanged on the day at 92.18 after it
failed to be substantiated.
Indeed, what hard news there was from the Bundesbank tended to be bearish.
Mr Helmut Schlesinger, the Bundesbank president, said inflation continued to
be the central bank's top priority. It was also disclosed that there would
be no news conference following today's meeting of the central bank's
council, which was interpreted as implying that there will be no rate cut.
In the sterling markets, dealers ignored the sharp appreciation of the pound
against both the D-Mark and dollar. Cash and futures prices implied that
there will be no imminent cut in UK base rates.
The March short sterling contract slipped 10 basis points to a low of 93.30,
but partially recovered to end at 93.35.
In the cash market, three-month money was unchanged at around 7 1/4 per
cent. One dealer said base rates were probably going down, but that the next
reduction may not be until after the spring.
</TEXT>
