<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JAN 93 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COPPER prices fell in dollar terms at the London Metal Exchange in what
dealers described as a consolidation following recent strong gains. The
three months price ended Dollars 10 lower at Dollars 2,350 a tonne. The
dealers noted that the market was still holding support levels. A late
technical sell-off snuffed out a partial rally in ALUMINIUM, the three
months position closing at Dollars Dollars 1,232 a tonne, down Dollars
13.25. Trading in aluminium was fairly volatile, with the market under early
pressure from option-linked selling. But it moved off its lows when Dollars
1,200 call (buying) strikes were exercised. NICKEL was easier following
early losses, although prices held near the middle of the day's range. Three
months metal closed at Dollars 6,297.50 a tonne, down Dollars 115, and fell
another Dollars 17.50 in after hours trading. SILVER prices were firmer,
with the cash position closing 4 cents higher at 371.50 cents a troy ounce.
But dealers were not expecting further gains. 'We did actually see quite
good selling most of the way up, so silver has probably done enough for
now,' one said.
Compiled from Reuters
</TEXT>
