<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JAN 93 / CS details bid for Volksbank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ZURICH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CS HOLDING, the parent company of Credit Suisse, is set to become
Switzerland's largest banking group in terms of assets following completion
of its agreed SFr1.6bn (Pounds 702m) bid for Swiss Volksbank.
CS is offering three of its registered shares for each SFr500 nominal
capital of the troubled Volksbank, which has been hurt in the past couple of
years by the slump in Swiss property prices and the depressed business
climate.
Mr Walter Ruegg, Volksbank chairman, said trading conditions deteriorated
last autumn just after the bank had set a rationalisation strategy, so the
board decided the best solution was to seek a strong partner.
Mr Rainer Gut, CS president, said the group was determined to maintain a
sufficient presence in its home market and, in particular, a dominant
position in the retail sector.
The takeover plan was welcomed by Mr Markus Lusser, president of the Swiss
National Bank, as a step towards eliminating excessive capacity in Swiss
banking. According to a study by consultants McKinsey, one in every 67 Swiss
inhabitants is a bank branch employee. This compares with one in every 102
people in the UK.
Mr Gut was vague about rationalisation plans, saying only that 'disagreeable
measures are sometimes inevitable'. Analysts said branches of the two banks
overlapped in more than 100 locations.
Investors were unenthusiastic about the deal, and CS Holding bearer shares
fell from SFr2,170 on Monday before the group indicated its interest, to
SFr1,980 at yesterday's close. Analysts said the issue of shares to pay for
the takeover would dilute CS earnings this year by about 10 per cent. On the
other hand, the purchase price discount to Volksbank's net asset value of
SFr2.2bn would boost CS equity.
Both CS and Union Bank of Switzerland (UBS), the country's largest bank, had
been invited by Volksbank last month to submit takeover bids. The Volksbank
board met on Tuesday to consider them after suspending trading in its shares
on Monday.
Volksbank must achieve shareholders' approval in March to convert itself
from a co-operative into a joint stock company.
Lex, Page 16
A giant among gnomes, Page 20
Markets, Page 29
</TEXT>
