<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JAN 93 / TSB Bank union calls one-day strike tomorrow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A NATIONAL one-day strike by workers at the retail branches and computer
centres of TSB Bank, England's fifth largest bank, will go ahead tomorrow,
after talks broke down yesterday.
Bifu, the banking, insurance and finance union, forecast large-scale support
for the strike at the 1,400 branches but TSB said it was unlikely that
branches would close. TSB said it would do everything possible to minimise
disruption to customers.
Fewer than a third of employees are likely to be involved in the action. Of
Bifu's 19,000 members in the banking side of TSB - of a total of 25,000
employees - 10,000 voted in the ballot, with 7,000 in favour of strike
action. White collar employees generally are more likely than manual workers
to cross picket lines.
Bifu has been negotiating with TSB for the past two years over a large
restructuring programme that has involved the loss of about 5,000 jobs.
However, talks at Acas, the arbitration, conciliation and advisory service,
broke down after TSB refused to guarantee no compulsory redundancies among
the further 1,000 job losses. TSB said yesterday: 'The vast majority of the
losses should be voluntary but we can make no guarantees to Bifu.'
Bifu is in a stronger position at TSB than at other banks because it has a
greater percentage of members among the workforce than at National
Westminster, Barclays and Lloyds Bank, where there are staff organisations.
Most of the thousands of redundancies in the banking sector have been
achieved by voluntary means. The recent threat of compulsory redundancies at
a time of acceleration of job cuts at other banks has caused concern among
staff associations. In November, Barclays' group staff union said they
'would not remain impassive' if there were compulsory redundancies.
Bifu intends to follow tomorrow's strike with a rolling programme of
selective walkouts around the country.
</TEXT>
