<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JAN 93 / Observer: Nothing ventured
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
So you want some venture capital? Knowing what not to do when seeking help
from a venture capitalist can be as important as knowing what to do,
according to Gresham Trust boss Trevor Jones, who has compiled his own handy
checklist.
You do not: ask your accountant to write the business plan; omit the last
set of audited accounts; forget to put in the management team's CVs; tell
the venture capitalist the terms you think he should offer; refuse to invest
in the business you run; talk about how much equity you are prepared to
'give away'; forget to say how much money you need and why; and assume all
investors want an exit in five years.
Observer offers Pounds 25 of 'seed capital' for an entrepreneur who can
suggest the seven best ways to persuade a venture capitalist to back you.
Answers by mail, or fax to 071-873 3926 - not telephone, please.
</TEXT>
