<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JAN 93 / Boat industry takes hopeful soundings: Richard Gourlay
reports that traditional Earls Court optimism has a ring of truth this year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN THE past four weeks, Marine Projects of Plymouth has sold three 65-ft
motor yachts at Pounds 650,000 each to Dutch, German and French clients.
At the other end of the scale, Hunter Boats of Essex reports that sales of
yachts at about Pounds 40,000 have picked up in the past three months.
After two battering years, exhibitors descending on Earls Court for this
week's London Boat Show will cling to such anecdotes. For the first time
since the market peaked in 1990, though, the optimism that is a fixture of
the show carries a ring of truth.
'There is reason to believe that we have hit bottom in the UK,' says Mr
David King, managing director of Marine Projects. 'We do now have a market
in the UK, whereas going back three months there was no market at all.'
Such signs of recovery remain faint and are not evident across the industry.
Many chandlers are facing great difficulties and have not even enjoyed the
benefit of owners re-equipping rather than trading in their boats.
Marina operators, who have lost some of boating's 1980s newcomers - or were
too late attracting them - are continuing to suffer as much as any company
in the property sector.
But builders with export markets have received a boost from the devaluation
of sterling in September. The greatest beneficiaries are likely to be the
large motor boat builders - Sunseekers, Marine Projects and Fairline Boats.
Smaller operators, in what has always been a highly fragmented industry, are
less likely to be able to bear the cost of exporting and will have to wait
for UK demand to pick up.
Devaluation will also reduce import penetration from continental Europe, in
particular from Scandinavia and Belgium, and from US companies, which some
UK builders say took advantage of an overvalued pound.
Nevertheless, there are storm clouds gathering over the industry in the very
countries that have helped keep the builders afloat. Exports already
accounted for Pounds 139m of total leisure boat sales of Pounds 238m in
1991. Now the vitality of some of those foreign markets is threatened.
Japan's economic troubles have drastically cut demand that was beginning to
take off after a switch in fashion away from golf. The downturn in the
German economy is threatening UK builders' largest single export market,
although so far they have not seen any fall in demand.
The last two years of recession has brought one clear benefit from UK boat
builders' point of view. In the 1980s, French boat builders, led by Beneteau
and Jeaneau, made great inroads into the traditional UK builders' market
share. They appeared to provide what the new rich wanted from their sailing.
That new mass market has now disappeared and British industry watchers
believe that French market share has fallen with it. As one UK builder
disparagingly says: 'The newcomers were attracted by the kind of boats that
sold well at boat shows' - where the French flourished.
If the rot in the UK industry has indeed been stopped, it would not be
before time. Many builders, such as Fairline and Marine Projects, have
trimmed their work-forces.
Some have lost 40 per cent of production over the past two years. Many more
have either gone out of business entirely or, like Westerly of Portsmouth,
have returned via the liquidators in much slimmed-down form.
Fairline, the only quoted boatbuilder in the UK, made a Pounds 500,000 loss
in the year to September and halved its dividend, although it booked a
record number of orders in November.
Sales by the industry as a whole, including leisure and commercial
boatbuilders, marina operators, sailmakers and suppliers of electronic
equipment, has shrunk by more than 25 per cent in two years.
In 1991 sales fell 19 per cent to Pounds 1.122bn with motor and sailing
yachts falling 16 per cent, according to the British Marine Industries
Federation.
Mr Tony Beechey, the federation's executive chairman, believes the fall
continued last year but at a slower pace, while 1993 will see overall sales
on a similar level. Equipment sales, however, have remained buoyant with
sales in 1991 of Pounds 284m, much of it exported.
As the boating industry gathered in London yesterday, there was even a
degree of optimism surrounding the European Commission's closure last month
of the much-used loophole that allowed buyers of boats to avoid paying value
added tax. 'The worst part of the VAT issue has been the lack of decisions
from Brussels,' says Mr Beechey.
No one is quite sure how sales will be affected. Some of the more bullish
salesmen are using VAT as part of the sales pitch. In a classic
demonstration of clutching at straws, one builder says the chancellor could
solve his funding problems by raising VAT rates in the spring. To avoid the
increase, yachtsmen should buy now.
Weathering the storm, Page 12
</TEXT>
<XX>
