</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JAN 93 / Labour PR campaign gains backbench boost
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR campaigners for electoral reform will receive a boost today with the
publication of a poll showing that two out of three of the party's MPs who
first took their seats after last year's election back some form of
proportional representation for the Commons.
The findings, taken from soundings by New Statesman and Society magazine of
52 of the 69 new MPs, appear to counter the view that the tide within the
parliamentary party is turning against change from the first-past-the-post
system.
The findings come on the eve of a two-day meeting in London of the party's
committee on electoral systems, which is set to examine elections to the
Commons for the first time.
The committee, chaired by Lord Plant, is divided over the issue, which PR
supporters are presenting as a litmus test of the party's readiness to take
radical steps to modernise and reform.
Last month Mr Neil Kinnock, the former party leader, came out for the first
time in favour of electoral reform after years of avoiding taking a public
stance on the question.
Some leading shadow cabinet figures closely associated with the modernising
faction in the party - including Mr Tony Blair, shadow home secretary, and
Mr Gordon Brown, shadow chancellor - have appeared increasingly sceptical of
PR. Mr John Smith, the leader, has refused to state his position.
The Plant committee is expected to submit a policy recommendation on the
issue to the national executive committee, possibly by March. But senior
party officials have indicated that a definitive leadership position may be
unlikely until after the local government elections in May.
The poll shows that 34 of the 52 MPs back reform. Thirteen were against and
five undecided. It is accompanied by a passionately argued article by Mr
Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary and a long-time advocate of
PR, warning that reform is vital to Labour's bid to return to office.
'There is no long-term future for Labour as a party of government if it
cannot re-establish local representation in the areas of fastest population
growth in the south, and there is no serious prospect of doing so without
PR,' he writes.
While criticising the handling of the issue during the 1992 election
campaign, Mr Cook points out that Labour won more votes in southern England
than in its heartlands in northern England, Yorkshire and Scotland yet
'ended up with only three Labour MPs to show for it'.
Meanwhile, opponents of PR claim that a majority of Labour MPs are opposed
to change, particularly after the Liberal Democrats' failure to join them in
voting against the government in the Maastricht treaty 'paving' debate in
November.
Mr Jeff Rooker MP, chairman of the Labour Campaign for Electoral Reform, is
planning to table a compromise proposal to the Plant committee aimed at
introducing a modified version of the Additional Member System, used in
Germany.
Under Mr Rooker's scheme, some 500 seats would continue to be elected on the
current basis, but 150 more would be allocated at regional level to 'best
losers' from other parties under a formula weighted to reflect each party's
overall electoral performance.
Any final decision on electoral systems will have to be approved by the
party conference in the autumn.
</TEXT>
