<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JAN 93 / Supermarkets have good season's sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TESCO and Kwik Save, the grocery chains, said yesterday they had traded well
over Christmas. They added to the growing belief among industry observers
that December was better than expected for food retailers.
Mr David Reid, finance director of Tesco, said the group had seen
like-for-like sales growth in its existing stores of 1.5 per cent, and total
sales growth, including new stores, of 9.5 per cent, over the four weeks to
January 2.
That was a 1-point improvement on the 8.5 per cent sales growth disclosed by
the company in its interim results in September.
Analysts said Tesco's announcement followed reports of like-for-like sales
growth of between 4 per cent and 5 per cent for J. Sainsbury; 3 per cent for
Argyll - owner of the Safeway chain - and 6.5 per cent for Wm Morrison.
Gateway is also believed to have surpassed its budget.
'From our point of view, it's very good news,' Mr Reid said. He added that
the figures would help to dispel rumours that performance had been
disappointing at Tesco's new stores.
Mr Reid added: 'But we would not want to over-hype things as to whether
recovery is on the way. You can get flurries at Budget time and at
Christmas.'
Mr Bill Currie, analyst with brokers Barclays de Zoete Wedd, said: 'It does
seem that food retailers saw a general pick-up over Christmas.'
BZW has upgraded its 1992 pre-tax profit forecasts for Tesco from Pounds
570m to Pounds 580m, and for J. Sainsbury from Pounds 735m to Pounds 740m.
Mr Keith Lovell, group finance and planning director with Kwik Save, the
discount food chain, said Christmas trading had been 'satisfactory, up to
expectations'.
