FT  07 JAN 93 / County Hall hotel proposal approved
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LAMBETH Council has approved a planning application by Shirayama Corporation
of Japan to turn County Hall, the former headquarters of the Greater London
Council, into a hotel.
Lambeth's planning committee gave permission subject to further
consideration later this month of the community benefits the developer will
provide.
The developer plans to convert the main building, which is across the River
Thames from the Houses of Parliament, into a 600-bed hotel with conference
and leisure facilities.
Shirayama says it will keep all the historic rooms intact and 'brought back
to their original splendour'. There will be a chapel and a health club in
the basement and a 24-hour public restaurant on the riverside terrace.
The council was advised to accept the planning application for several
reasons, including the need for high-quality hotel accommodation in London
and the employment potential.
