<PROFILE>_AN-DAGB2ABGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930107
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JAN 93 / The Braer Disaster: Islanders see fears fulfilled
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'A DISASTER like this has been on everyone's mind for the last 20 years,'
says Mr James Moncrieff, a Shetlander. 'It's ironic that it turned out to be
a passing tanker that caused it.'
The Shetland islands have had a tempestuous relationship with the oil
industry since North Sea oil was discovered in the 1970s and it was decided
to bring it ashore at Sullom Voe at the north end of the main island.
For years the Shetlanders negotiated arrangements with the oil companies
that would make them one of the more prosperous parts of Britain, and which
would guard against the destruction of their environment.
The Shetlanders were concerned not just that their gaunt scenery should be
disfigured as little as possible by the oil industry's installations. They
were also deeply worried that at some stage there would be an environmental
catastrophe involving tankers using Sullom Voe.
In the event, there has been only one serious spillage, in an accident
involving a tanker at the oil and gas terminal, which opened in 1981. That
was not on anything like the scale of the Braer disaster, but because of the
constant awareness of the threat of an environmental tragedy, Shetland,
which has a population of 22,000, has always been prepared and well equipped
to deal with oil pollution.
As disaster has been a lingering nightmare, many people in Shetland have
reacted with resignation to the fact that it has now struck, albeit from an
unexpected quarter. But there has also been anger that the Braer was
travelling close to the islands and questions have been raised about the
standards of seamanship of the tanker's crew.
That surfaced at a press conference yesterday morning when Mr Willie Tait,
the Shetland Islands councillor for the Sumburgh area, blamed the crew of
the Braer for the disaster and said that a British crew would not have
abandoned its ship while it was in such danger of crashing with devastating
effect on to the rocks.
While many Shetlanders are dismayed by the threat to the birds and sealife
caused by the pollution, and by the casualties they have already suffered,
the biggest economic threat is to the fishing and fish farming industries.
In spite of oil wealth, Shetland still makes much of its living from fish.
Almost a third of the islands' 10,000-strong labour force works in the fish
industry, including fishermen, fish processors and salmon farmers.
Mr John Goodlad, secretary of the Shetland Fishermen's Association, said:
'We are more dependent on fish than any other part of the EC. Without
fishing, the future of this community is doubtful.'
Fortunately, with the oil slick so far confined to a fairly small area
around the wreck of the Braer, there has been no impact on the fishing
grounds and the islands' salmon farms have not been affected.
Salmon farming became an important industry in Shetland in the 1980s and
Shetland produces about a quarter of the 40,000 tonnes of salmon reared by
salmon farms in Scotland.
The Shetland salmon farming industry is reckoned to account for about Pounds
35m of the Pounds 80m turnover of the islands' fishing industry.
Mr Moncrieff, who is chief executive of the Shetland Salmon Farmers'
Association, said: 'We are very afraid of what would happen if the oil slick
entered the voes (inlets) on the west coast where most of the salmon farms
are.'
The cages in which the salmon are reared would be highly vulnerable to oil
pollution. The nearest voe containing fish farms is at East Burra, only 13
miles from the scene of the disaster.
The salmon farmers hope the emergency teams will erect booms to prevent the
oil entering the voes, but until it is clear where the oil will go there is
little to be done than prepare the booms. Two small booms have been erected
near the wreck so far.
About 1,500 metres of boom material is on the islands and a further 5,000 to
7,000 metres is arriving early today by ferry from Aberdeen, having been
rushed from England.
A more immediate worry for the fishermen and fish farmers is the chemical
dispersants that are being sprayed on the oil at and around the wrecked
tanker.
Mr Moncrieff said: 'The mixture of oil and dispersant creates an emulsion
which goes right down through the water, whereas without dispersant the oil
stays on the surface. This means that with the dispersant the oil may cause
more damage than if it had been left.'
Both he and Mr Goodlad believe that with Shetland being at the confluence of
the Atlantic Ocean and the North Sea, the best action to take where the oil
slick is outside confined waters is to leave the forces of nature to
disperse the oil.
</TEXT>
<XX>
