<DATE>930107
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JAN 93 / US budget casts Clinton's goal into doubt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT-ELECT Bill Clinton cannot fulfil his campaign promise of halving
the budget deficit within four years without imposing strict controls on
popular 'entitlement' programmes such as federal health care, according to
Mr Richard Darman, the Bush administration's budget director.
On unchanged policies, the budget deficit would not fall substantially below
Dollars 300bn (Pounds 194.8bn) for the foreseeable future, a final skeleton
budget from the Bush administration indicated yesterday.
Mr Darman's figures show the deficit rising to Dollars 327.3bn this fiscal
year, declining modestly to Dollars 266.4bn in fiscal 1996 and then rising
again to Dollars 319.8bn in fiscal 1998.
This compares with projections in last year's budget that the deficit would
decline to just over Dollars 200bn by 1996.
The difference reflects much less optimistic revenue projections in this
year's budget, partly as a result of more realistic growth assumptions.
Projected revenue over five years is more than Dollars 200bn lower than
assumed last January.
However, Mr Clinton's advisers said Mr Darman was still underplaying the
extent of the fiscal deterioration by assuming that discretionary domestic
spending would be frozen in cash terms from 1995 onwards, an unrealistic
assumption. They said prospective deficits were Dollars 50bn-Dollars 60bn
higher than assumed at last month's economic conference in Little Rock and
unless checked could soar above Dollars 400bn towards the end of the decade.
Mr Darman warned that efforts to curb the deficit by stimulating growth were
doomed to fail. On his figures, in the absence of tax and spending measures,
a halving of the deficit to about Dollars 150bn by fiscal 1996 would require
four years of real growth averaging 4.4-4.8 per cent a year, a 'heroic'
assumption.
Mr Darman noted that Mr Clinton had also promised not to raise taxes on
people earning less than Dollars 200,000 a year and to use any savings from
health care cost controls to extend benefits for millions of uninsured
workers. Health care savings thus could not be used to cut the deficit.
These constraints created 'a circle that cannot be squared'.
In the absence of tax increases on middle-income families, deficit reduction
required a cap on all mandatory 'entitlement' programmes, such as health
care for the elderly and poor, with most of the savings allocated to deficit
reduction.
If increases in mandatory spending were restricted to inflation plus an
allowance for population growth, Dollars 409bn could be saved over five
years and nearly Dollars 2,000bn over a decade, according to Mr Darman's
figures. There was no scope for similar savings in any other part of the
budget.
In a carefully phrased reaction yesterday, Mr Clinton said the 'endless
pattern of rising deficits must stop. . . . We must make the difficult
choices that will allow us both to close the budget deficit and the
investment deficit that together threaten our future.'
However, the latest gloomy figures underline his fiscal dilemma. He wants to
increase federal investment spending sharply without raising taxes on the
middle classes. Yet he has not yet shown any appetite for curbing popular
entitlement programmes.
The two fastest growing are Medicare and Medicaid, the health care
programmes for the elderly and poor. According to yesterday's budget,
Medicare spending is set to rise from Dollars 129.9bn this year to Dollars
235.8bn by fiscal 1998; Medicaid from Dollars 80.5bn to Dollars 156.4bn.
Mr Darman was at pains yesterday to emphasise the strength of the economy
the Republicans were handing over. Real output had risen for seven quarters
and was set to grow 3 per cent this year. Inflation would be just over 3 per
cent and unemployment would fall to 7 per cent by year end.
