<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JAN 93 / Finance minister pledges continued support for punt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Bertie Ahern, the Irish finance minister, denied yesterday the outgoing
government planned to abandon its defence of the punt and said it would be
up to the new administration to review its exchange rate policy.
A new Fianna Fail-Labour coalition is expected to be formed next week.
The minister said on Irish radio that the present government had
'unequivocally and consistently supported the existing parity of the Irish
pound and has done so simply because it is the best policy for the long-term
benefit of the Irish economy. I have. . . argued that since the Maastricht
treaty was defeated in the Danish referendum on June 2.'
Mr Ahern said he could not pre-empt or speak on behalf of the incoming
government. This would be 'entirely wrong'. He stressed: 'I have no reason
at this time to believe that the new government, if it is Fianna Fail and
the Labour party, would change that policy.'
He added that a report in the Financial Times on Tuesday had 'grossly
misinterpreted' statements made by him on Monday evening in which he said:
'I said I was prepared to hold the line until the end of the year. That has
now passed. If the system does not correct itself. . . the pressures on
industry are something that cannot be lived with indefinitely'.
He had emphasised his continued opposition to a unilateral devaluation, but
added this was an issue 'the new government will have to look at very early
on'.
Mr Albert Reynolds, the prime minister, told parliament on Monday he hoped
to be in a position to form a new coalition government by early next week
'if budgetary matters can be agreed'. His Fianna Fail party and Labour have
been negotiating terms for forming a coalition since the November 25 general
election, in which no party won an overall majority.
