<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JAN 93 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A DAY split into two distinct halves saw the futures market reach a new
all-time high only to end the day in ignominious retreat, writes Christopher
Price.
The opening of trading on the March FT-SE future contract was dominated by
hopes of a cut in German interest rates at the Bundesbank meeting tomorrow.
March, which opened at 2,882, moved smartly forward on the speculation,
which raised hopes for a further easing of UK rates.
Strong short sterling and firm gilts also combined to squeeze March higher
through a busy morning period, before the contract reached an historical
high of 2,898 around midday.
However, the mood changed for the afternoon when the European interest rate
markets weakened and the German rate cut hopes diminished. A leading US
house led the way, selling the future down, helped by rumours of a large
rights issue from BP.
By late afternoon, March had dropped to 2,850, its low of the day, before
rallying at the close to finish at 2,856, a 10-point premium to its fair
value of around 15. Volume was a credible 9,549 contracts.
Volume was also healthy in the options market, where 33,322 contracts were
traded, of which the FT-SE 100 contract was responsible for 9,339 lots.
Marks and Spencer was the top traded stock option at 1,332, followed by Blue
Circle at 1,324.
</TEXT>
