<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JAN 93 / International Capital Markets: Overseas companies raise more
funds in US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FOREIGN companies have been tapping the US capital markets for funds in
greater numbers than ever before, according to a study released yesterday by
the Securities Industry Association.
Annualised data compiled by the SIA suggest that total foreign securities
sold in the US primary market in 1992 will approach a record Dollars 67.9bn,
24 per cent more than the Dollars 54.8bn sold the previous year, and seven
times the total sold in 1985.
The SIA said that a number of factors were behind the boom in foreign
issues, including low US interest rates, a favourable dollar exchange rate,
increased demand for foreign debt and equity from US investors, and the
lowering of some regulatory barriers, especially the introduction of rule
144a which has made it easier to sell securities in the private market.
Foreign issuers were also attracted by the size, liquidity and efficiency of
the US capital markets, which last year raised a record Dollars 381.4bn in
straight debt and equity for US and overseas companies.
Last year, foreign issuance of equity and debt was almost evenly distributed
between the public and private markets.
The SIA study, however, believes the use of public markets would be
significantly greater but for the costs and hurdles of registering
publicly-issued securities with the government, which it says remain too
onerous for many foreign companies.
Among overseas issuers of equity in the US, UK companies were the most
active last year, thanks primarily to the Dollars 1.1bn issue of American
Depositary Receipts in July by Wellcome, the pharmaceutical group.
Mexico was the next largest foreign issuer. Again one company, Telefonos de
Mexico, which sold Dollars 758m of ADRs in May, dominated.
