<DATE>930106
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JAN 93 / Volksbank agrees SFr1.64bn takeover: CS Holding's move opens
way for Swiss rationalisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CS HOLDING, the parent company of Credit Suisse, Switzerland's third-largest
bank, is to acquire Swiss Volksbank, the fifth-largest, in an agreed share
exchange deal that values Volksbank at SFr1.64bn (Dollars 1.14bn).
The two said in a statement last night that the acquisition aimed to
'enhance the earning power and competitiveness' of both Volksbank and Credit
Suisse. It would also contribute to further specialisation among the banking
subsidiaries within the CS Holding group.
The statement said that Credit Suisse would concentrate on international
activities, securities underwriting and major corporate and institutional
clients.
Volksbank would keep its identity, focusing on business with small and
medium-sized companies and private clients within Switzerland. 'At the same
time, Volksbank and Credit Suisse will assume a leading position in the
Swiss retail banking market.'
Analysts have observed that there is considerable duplication between the
branch networks of the two banks, and the statement said 'both banks will,
from the outset, take steps to improve organisational efficiency by
rationalising wherever possible'.
Under the terms of the deal, CS will offer to exchange three of its
registered shares for SFr500 worth of Volksbank equity. The purchase price
is a substantial premium on the SFr1.1bn market capitalisation of Volksbank
before the shares were suspended on Monday morning.
CS said last night that it did not hold any Volksbank shares.
The takeover constitutes a big step towards the rationalisation of
Switzerland's bloated retail banking sector.
The word 'overbanked' is trotted out in many countries these days, as
profit-squeezed banks seek to justify their cost-cutting programmes. But few
can outdo Switzerland in this regard.
According to a recent study by McKinsey &amp; Co, the international consultants,
there is one bank branch in the country for every 67 inhabitants. This
compares with one for every 102 people in Britain, one per 136 in France and
one per 105 in Germany.
The McKinsey study also claimed that the return on equity invested in retail
banking in Switzerland in 1990 averaged a negative 37 per cent.
For a long time, Swiss banks could tolerate subsidising their retail
activities. Most of them are universal banks and they were making lush
profits in other sectors, especially in securities trading where commissions
were fixed.
But with the collapse of fixed commissions and other cozy conventions in the
past few years, banks have had to seek profits from all their activities.
The pressure on the retail sector has intensified even more in the past two
years as many mortgage loans have gone sour in the recession.
Swiss banking leaders have thus become ever more confident in predicting a
big shakeout among the country's 600-odd banks. Mr Robert Studer, chief
executive of Union Bank of Switzerland (UBS), the country's largest, said
last March that he could see 100 of them disappearing in the next decade.
Other analysts talk of 20,000 of the industry's 115,000 jobs being lost in
the next few years.
The shakeout is already well under way. Credit Suisse snapped up Bank Leu,
the country's fifth-largest bank, after a hostile bid in late 1990. Swiss
Bank Corporation (SBC), the second-largest, last year consolidated its
control of Banca della Svizzera Italiana. Several small regional banks have
merged with each other or been absorbed by big banks in the past year. The
two cantonal banks in Geneva are set to merge at the end of this year.
The Credit Suisse takeover of Volksbank will open the way for the biggest
single step yet. This is because the branch networks of both are very large
and overlap virtually completely.
Most of the 191 Volksbank branches could be eliminated without loss of
market coverage. The operation will be long, costly and will generate a lot
of political flak, as was shown in the slump of the bearer shares of CS
Holding by SFr70 yesterday to SFr2,100 following the group's confirmation
that it was interested in Volksbank. But Mr Rainer Gut, the CS Holding
chairman, is known for his thick skin.
There are other possible reasons for Credit Suisse's interest in Volksbank.
In his speech last March, UBS's Mr Studer said, perhaps mischievously, that
one of the big three might ultimately decide to withdraw from retail
banking. Analysts instantly concluded that he was referring to Credit
Suisse, the smallest of the three.
Credit Suisse leaders have since been at pains to emphasise their total
commitment to retail banking, and Mr Gut has even hinted on occasion that
the group might contemplate an acquisition in the retail sector.
It will also add legitimacy to the costly decision in 1987 to form a holding
structure for the CS group. Last night, the group confirmed that its banking
subsidiaries would be more specialised in the future with Volksbank
concentrating on small business lending in Switzerland.
The takeover will enable Credit Suisse to close substantially the gap in
assets between it and its two larger rivals. At the end of June, 1992, UBS
had total assets of SFr258.8bn, SBC SFr201bn, Credit Suisse SFr163.7bn and
Volksbank SFr48.5bn.
Although Volksbank's profits have tumbled in recent years, it is still well
capitalised, with a 10.2 per cent capital ratio under the BIS guidelines. Mr
Hans Kaufmann, head of Swiss research at Bank Julius Baer in Zurich,
estimates that a streamlined Volksbank could make annual profits of up to
SFr300m.
Analysts have been intrigued for months by a sudden surge in trading in
Volksbank shares that took place in the early autumn, when the price bounced
back from a low of SFr610 in early September to over SFr770 by the end of
October.
On October 28, the bank announced it would convert its capital structure
from that of a co-operative, with one vote per shareholder regardless of the
size of his holding, to a joint stock company. Terms of the conversion, due
to be approved by shareholders in April, have not yet been revealed.
There are no laws in Switzerland requiring potential bidders to reveal their
holdings once they have gone over a certain level.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>CS Holding.
    Swiss Volksbank.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>CHZ  Switzerland, West Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
