<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JAN 93 / County council job cuts threat: Tens of thousands of posts
at risk, mainly in north and Midlands
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS and CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COUNTY COUNCILS are poised to make tens of thousands of redundancies over
the next few months, adding to the wave of job losses announced before
Christmas by the large city authorities.
County councils are currently discussing draft budgets for next year.
Prospects are growing of large-scale job losses in those counties, mainly in
the Midlands and the north, which face capping by the government if their
spending rises by more than a tiny margin on this year.
With education by far the biggest responsibility of counties, that will mean
widespread teacher redundancies, and large cuts in spending on schools.
Humberside has advised the Department of Employment that 1,000 job losses
could be in the offing, and it has warned schools that funding for their
devolved budgets next year could be as much as 7.5 per cent down on this
year.
Derbyshire has advised that 2,000 job losses are in prospect, 1,000 of them
in education, unless the government revises its criteria for capping council
spending.
According to the Association of County Councils, a further 12 of England's
39 county councils are constrained to a spending increase of less than two
per cent above this year's level, placing them in a similar predicament.
Mr Martin Doughty, Labour leader of Derbyshire county council, said: 'The
government's spending assessments are deeply unfair. We have no reserves
left, yet our spending is being capped at only 1.75 per cent above this
year. Unless it is changed, there will have to be big job losses.'
County councils in the south-east are less badly affected. Most have been
allowed to increase their spending by more than the prevailing inflation
rate, since their spending for this year is generally well below the capping
level. However, counties in the north claim that they are also benefiting
unfairly from changes to government spending assessments.
London boroughs and smaller district councils in the north are also shedding
staff in large numbers.
The London borough of Lambeth is to lose 1,000 posts. North Tyneside council
will today issue compulsory redundancy notices, and aims cut out 1,100 of
the 9,500 people employed in April 1992.
To the surprise of North Tyneside's leaders, 700 employees have volunteered
to leave, substantially reducing the compulsory redundancies required. The
redundancies come on top of a loss of 1,000 jobs between April 1990 and
1992.
Moreover, the council, which in 1991 lost a national test case legal battle
over the enhanced voluntary severance scheme it was then offering, is now
giving volunteers no more than the statutory terms to which they are
entitled.
Of the 700 volunteers, who include 200 teachers, the majority are over-50s
taking early retirement. They qualify for enhanced pension and lump sum
payments on top of their redundancy payment.
Average redundancy payments made to the volunteers are Pounds 5,600 for
white collar staff and Pounds 2,200 for manual workers.
</TEXT>
<XX>
