<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JAN 93 / Pit closures fight stepped up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH and DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FURTHER CHALLENGES to force a resumption of work at threatened pits and to
refund lost earnings of laid-off miners were mounted yesterday as unions
intensified their campaign to keep mines open.
Following meetings at the Trades Union Congress in London yesterday, mine
and rail unions also said they would next week consider a national
stay-at-home day of action in protest at threatened pit closures, job losses
and privatisation.
That could cause friction with other unions and the TUC, which is planning a
day of action next month when TUC officials expect unemployment to exceed
3m.
Mr Arthur Scargill, president of the National Union of Mineworkers, said he
had written to the prime minister saying that Mr Michael Heseltine, trade
and industry secretary, was personally liable for more than Pounds 100m paid
by the government for miners' severance payments since the announcement in
October that 31 pits were to be closed.
Mr Scargill's contention follows the High Court judgment in December that
the government had acted unlawfully in deciding to close 31 pits without a
proper review. He told Mr Major that taxpayers' money had been spent
unlawfully on severance payments and that Mr Heseltine was in the same
position as local councillors or company directors who had incurred
liabilities for illegal acts.
Mr Scargill also demanded the resumption of production at the 10 pits
earmarked for immediate closure, and the refunding of lost earnings for
miners laid off on basic pay since October.
The more important legal argument now centres on the 10 pits, which were
excluded from the Department of Trade and Industry review of the original
closure decision.
The unions insist that the High Court ruling means a version of the
industry's Modified Colliery Review Procedure has to be implemented for the
10 pits. This means it could be early summer before a decision is made.
The High Court ruling appears to give the unions the right to reject the
government's decision to appoint John T. Boyd, the US mining consultancy, as
the independent reviewer of the 10 pits.
Mr Scargill said yesterday the unions would reject Boyd and quoted from the
ruling: 'It is for British Coal and the unions to decide how . . . an
independent scrutiny should be conducted and who should conduct it.'
The unions also argue that work should resume at the 10 pits or it may be
impossible to resume profitable production when the review is complete. The
TUC claims that the cost of keeping the pits open but not producing coal is
nearly Pounds 5m a week.
The government is determined not to start coal production. British Coal said
production would stop next week at Betws colliery in Wales which is the only
one of the 10 where it has been continuing.
</TEXT>
