<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JAN 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Big programme of the night is Clive James - Fame in the Twentieth Century on
BBC 1 at 9.30. In antiquity, rulers knew about exploiting their images in
metal, stone, or wood. However, James's theory is that with the advent of
the moving camera the nature of fame was profoundly altered. Tonight's
line-up of most famous faces ever includes Charlie Chaplin and Rudolf
Valentino.
Time is running out for Inspector Morse, the man who more than any other
fictional character has put 20th century Oxford on the map. Tonight sees the
first of the final series (ITV, 8.00). The remarkable thing about Morse
(played, I need hardly say, by John Thaw) is that the screen character is so
satisfying, and the chap in Colin Dexter's novels so utterly pedestrian.
In an ironic contrast between youth of today and ..youth of today, you can
start with Def II's Reportage: Screen Generation on BBC 2 at 6.50, and
grieve for the children who become murderous zombies (sorry, I mean
'socially dysfunctional') from too many video games. Then contemplate
serried ranks of well-scrubbed youth in Choir of the Year (BBC 2 at 7.30.)
</TEXT>
