<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JAN 93 / People: Knox joins Bank of Scotland board
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Bank of Scotland, which says its policy is to make 'interesting but
competent appointments regardless of sex and age', has chosen Lesley Knox as
a non-executive director, the first woman to join the board of Scotland's
second biggest bank.
At 39, Knox is going on for 20 years younger than most of the other
directors, who include Sir Bob Reid, Sir Alick Rankin and John Menzies. She
is the second non-executive appointee since Bruce Pattullo took over the
governorship in mid-1991. In that year three non-executive directors
retired; Sir Alistair Grant, chairman of Argyll, joined with effect from
last August. Its bigger rival, the Royal Bank of Scotland, has had a woman -
Elizabeth Nelson - on the board for the past five years.
Now running the institutional investment management side of Kleinwort
Benson, Knox became a director in 1986 - making her the first female
director at any merchant bank in the City.
Her connections with the Bank of Scotland are on one level sentimental in
that it was the first company in which she owned any shares. Aged 18, she
turned up to her first agm: 'I thought I would go along to see what
happened,' says Knox, who was brought up in Edinburgh.
Since then, when working in the corporate finance division of KB, she was on
the team that advised the Edinburgh-based bank when it was considering the
purchase of a US regional bank four years ago. Company secretary Hugh Young
recalls how impressed the board had been with a presentation she made to
them at the time. 'With (the) Cadbury (recommendations on corporate
governance), the age of directors is going to drop. Under our regulations,
they can carry on to 70, but I don't think they will in future,' he adds.
Subsequently, through her corporate advisory work, Knox has met a number of
the other directors, including Thomas Hutchison, deputy governor of the bank
and a non-executive at Cadbury Schweppes. 'I hope they know I'll be making a
vociferous contribution,' she says.
</TEXT>
