<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JAN 93 / How managers' styles differ: British Psychological Society
Conference
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH executives manage from experience, their peers in Korea use manuals,
while Iranians are guided by national beliefs, according to a survey of
almost 2,000 decision makers in 16 countries.
Only the Finns and the Dutch are more individualistic and independent in
decision-making than UK managers, delegates were told yesterday at the
British Psychological Society's occupational psychology conference in
Brighton.
The survey, which was completed by at least 100 managers in each country,
also found that Portuguese managers were likely to rely on guidance from
superiors and that managers in Nigeria tended to make their decisions by the
book, using company manuals or rule books. The research, funded by the
Japanese photocopier and camera producer, Canon, found that Japanese
managers relied partly on their own experience and training and partly on
their superiors, as did the Americans, Australians and South Africans.
Dr Peter Smith, reader in social psychology at Sussex University's School of
Social Sciences, said: 'Multinational companies need to be very aware of the
different preferences as to how decisions might be taken in different parts
of the world.'
He said: 'Outside of western countries, we found much more reliance on
superiors, much more reliance on manuals on rules of procedure and in some
countries, particularly Muslim countries, people said they rely on beliefs
which are widespread nationally.'
The survey suggests managers in all countries believe decisions based on
their own experience and training usually give the best results.
Management, Page 9
</TEXT>
