<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JAN 93 / Value of stress courses is queried: British Psychological
Society Conference
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STRESS management courses may be 'money for old rope', two senior
psychologists told the conference yesterday.
That is because stress is a confused concept that reveals little about
employees' difficulties at work, according to Ms Shirley Reynolds, clinical
psychologist with the Medical Research Council at Sheffield University, and
Dr Rob Briner, occupational psychology lecturer at London University's
Birkbeck College.
Dr Briner said: 'If we do believe these courses are money for old rope, then
in the world of business psychology that is not unusual.'
Ms Reynolds said: 'I certainly would not spend money on them, but on the
other hand many organisations spend money on graphologists (handwriting
analysts) in recruitment - I wouldn't do that, either.'
They told delegates: 'The academic and practitioner communities of
occupational psychologists have collectively ignored, avoided or denied the
theoretical and conceptual confusion and the empirical inconsistencies in
the occupational stress literature.'
Such selective reading of the literature led psychologists to make
'over-optimistic' claims about the effectiveness of many stress management
strategies.
Ms Reynolds said: 'If there is no clear link between stress and poor
performance at work, then interventions which are based on that assumption
are unlikely to be particularly helpful.'
She said: 'Most stress management courses are based on a 'feel good' factor.
Some people certainly do experience distress at work but just sending along
10 or 12 people who have nothing wrong with them is unlikely to deliver
anything more than very short-term benefits because there is nothing to
cure.'
Job satisfaction declines significantly in the aftermath of privatisation,
but recovers after subsequent restructuring, a study suggests.
'Privatised companies should restructure as soon as possible instead of
waiting a few months, as is more usual,' Professor Cary Cooper of Manchester
School of Management told the conference.
His study of 620 employees of a privatised water company found that job
satisfaction declined after privatisation.
</TEXT>
