<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JAN 93 / Prescott call adds to pressure on Smith
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRESSURE on Mr John Smith to put a firm stamp on the Labour leadership
mounted further yesterday as Mr John Prescott, shadow transport secretary,
called for the party to make a decisive shift back to conviction politics.
The implicit criticism of Mr Smith's six-month tenure as opposition leader
came in a recorded BBC television programme - due to be broadcast today -
echoing widespread media criticism of Labour's post-election performance. Mr
Prescott said the British people responded positively to 'politicians with
convictions' who were committed to ideas.
'That is why Thatcher was quite popular with a lot of people,' he said.
'They knew where they stood with her. They don't know where they stand with
Labour on some essential questions - you have to spell it out.'
Mr Prescott's comments will anger many senior Labour figures who argue that,
with an election probably some four years away, Mr Smith is right to take
his time reforming the party and its policies.
Even so, the comments reflect the anxiety of Labour supporters on all sides
of the party, many of whom are demanding a swifter response to last April's
fourth successive election defeat.
Mr Prescott is viewed widely as a representative of traditional Labour
supporters who oppose efforts by so-called modernisers to revamp the party's
image. Some modernisers will nevertheless tacitly endorse his call for a
more rigorous style of leadership.
The revelation this week of further details of a confidential Labour opinion
poll under-lining the extent of public disenchantment with the party has
served only to emphasise the distance Labour must travel to win a real
chance of office.
A fresh effort to persuade a sceptical Labour leadership to adopt a policy
of electoral reform for elections to the Commons will be launched tomorrow.
But there are signs that the tide is turning against changing the
first-past-the-post system.
Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary and a long-standing
advocate of proportional representation, will tomorrow put the case for
reform in an article in New Statesman and Society. Labour officials insisted
last night that it was still far too early to predict the final conclusions
of the Plant committee on electoral systems.
Observers increasingly believe that widely diverging views across the party
mean that in order to avert a damaging internal schism the status quo is
unlikely to be changed.
</TEXT>
