FT  06 JAN 93 / Radio 4 listeners to march on BBC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RADIO 4 listeners, angry at the prospect of losing their favourite
programmes on long wave, have again threatened to march on Broadcasting
House.
Original plans for a march were cancelled in October after BBC executives
persuaded the organiser, Mr Nick MacKinnon, a Winchester schoolmaster, that
the protesters had prevailed. The march is now planned for April.
The BBC governors postponed the planned launch of a 24-hour news service on
long wave until April 1994. The BBC also promised that the new service would
not go ahead unless 'the transmission arrangements for Radio 4 meet the
listeners' needs throughout the UK'. New booster FM transmitters are being
built.
Miss Rachel Mawhood, the new UK co-ordinator of the Radio 4 Campaign, is
sceptical about BBC promises, saying FM is difficult to receive in many
parts of the country. She listens to Radio 4 programmes on long wave to get
better reception even though she lives in the Greenwich area of London.
'They can put 24-hour news on FM or Radio 5 if they want to,' Miss Mawhood
said.
The BBC argues that Gulf war coverage demonstrated the need for a 24-hour
news service that will also carry the main Radio 4 current affairs
programmes such as Today.
On Saturday in the Call To Account programme on Radio 4, Mr Michael Green,
the channel controller, said the BBC wanted to add a service that would be
of value to listeners.
'The question is where do we put it,' Mr Green said, apparently suggesting
that the issue was not entirely cut and dried. Mr Green insisted it would
not be practical to put the news service on Radio 5.
View of broadcasting, Page 13
</TEXT>
