<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JAN 93 / Conventions will limit claims against insurers: Insurance
group fears heavy loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'AT THE moment we are looking at a heavy loss, but if the vessel breaks up,
this will be a major catastrophe,' said Mr Michael Thorpe of Skuld, the
Norwegian protection and indemnity (P&amp;I) club, which provides liability
insurance for Bergvall &amp; Hudner Ship Management, manager of the stricken
Braer.
He said that under the terms of two international conventions to which the
UK is a signatory, potential insurance claims to meet the cost of the
pollution clean-up and related losses should be contained to a maximum of
Dollars 35m (Pounds 23m).
Liability for the Braer is limited to about Dollars 17m under the Civil
Liability Convention - funded by tanker owners - and to between Dollars 33m
and Dollars 35m under the International Oil Pollution Compensation Fund.
London marine insurers and brokers said that for the limits to be breached,
claimants would need to show that the vessel's owners were, at least, guilty
of gross negligence.
Friends of the Earth, the environment group, is urging the introduction of
unlimited liability for tanker accidents.
Of the potential Dollars 35m payout, Skuld, the fourth-biggest P&amp;I club with
premium income of more than Dollars 150m, would pay Dollars 2m. Sixteen P&amp;I
clubs, owned by shipping fleets, would meet the next Dollars 13m.
Claims above Dollars 15m would fall on the reinsurance market, largely
through a scheme negotiated by the P&amp;I clubs with Lloyd's syndicates and
London market companies. Reinsurers would cover claims up to Dollars 500m if
convention limits were breached.
</TEXT>
