<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JAN 93 / Tougher regulation urged for tankers: Safety standards at
sea criticised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GROUNDING of the tanker Braer off Shetland yesterday has led to calls
for the UK to tighten its restrictions on allowing ageing tankers into
environmentally sensitive areas.
The Merchant Navy Officers' Union said a steep decline in maritime safety
standards had resulted in a huge increase in the number of sub-standard
ships in British waters.
The Oil Pollution Act, which was passed in the US in August 1990 in the
aftermath of the Exxon Valdez tragedy, will phase out the use of older,
single-hulled tankers at US ports over the next 15 years. It also restricts
the use of single-hulled vessels in environmentally fragile areas.
The Braer was carrying 619,300 barrels of oil - more than double the 300,000
barrels spilt by the Exxon Valdez, which ran aground off the coast of Alaska
in 1989.
The Braer, which was built in 1975, had been in good condition with no
previous record of serious accidents, according to Mr Norman Hook at Lloyd's
Casualties.
But, like most of the world's ageing tanker fleet, the Braer was a
single-hulled vessel without the added protection of an outer casing, which
minimises the risk of oil spills.
Under rules introduced by the United Nations' International Maritime
Organisation in March last year, this type of tanker cannot now be built,
and all new tankers must have double hulls.
Mr Roger Kohn of the institute said: 'There is some concern that the
existing tanker fleet is getting older and there is a big gap between
pollution control standards on old and new vessels.'
The institute rules require that all existing tankers be brought up to the
same pollution control standards as newly built double-hulled vessels by
1995.
That involves extensive refits to the world's fleet of tankers, estimated to
cost Dollars 80m (Pounds 52m) a vessel.
The institute has rejected US insistence that all existing tankers be fitted
with double hulls in favour of retaining more options such as refitting
tankers with hydrostatic controls which equalise the pressure in the oil
tank and outside in order to minimise oil spills.
Mr Chris Smith, Labour's spokesman on environmental protection, asked why
the UK government had not followed the US administration in learning the
lessons from the Exxon Valdez disaster and tightened controls on oil
tankers.
'I insist they (the government) now adopt the rules the United States have
already implemented,' he said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
