<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JAN 93 / Wildlife at risk as oil spreads: Braer spillage 'potentially
catastrophic'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE environmental impact of the wrecked Braer oil tanker near Sumburgh Head
in Shetland was described last night by the World Wide Fund for Nature as
'potentially catastrophic'.
Lord Caithness, the shipping minister, said after briefing the prime
minister: 'We have got the dispersants, the planes and the tugs. We are very
clear what we are going to do. At the moment the sea is doing the job for
us.
'Nature has taken over,' he continued. 'It is perhaps a good thing there is
a gale because that will help to diversify the oil, break it down and get
rid of it. If it calms down, we will try to spray tomorrow.' He said there
would be a wide-ranging inquiry into the disaster.
Mr Jonathan Wills, a wildlife expert living on Shetland, said such a
shipwreck had been feared for 15 years: 'This was the disaster that was not
supposed to happen.'
Ms Sian Pullen, marine conservation officer with the wildlife fund, said the
organisation was asking for special routeing for certain types of tankers
around environmentally sensitive areas. 'Questions should be asked about why
a ship carrying such a hazardous substance was navigating through this area
in dangerous conditions,' she said.
The southern tip of Shetland, which has four sites designated as having
special scientific interest, is recognised as an internationally important
area for seabirds and marine life. A chain of life from microscopic marine
organisms to birds, porpoises and whales is at risk from pollution.
Ms Nancy Harrison, marine policy officer for the Royal Society for the
Protection of Birds, said: 'This is a potential major disaster for wildlife.
Questions must be asked why a single-hulled tanker, which is banned around
sensitive coastlines in other countries, is allowed to be in one of
Britain's most vulnerable sites for marine wildlife.'
She said that thousands of seabirds might be lost in the oil spillage, but
that the catastrophe would have been worse had the ship been wrecked in
summer, when more birds would have been nesting on shore. 'In a sense, we're
lucky it isn't summer, but I don't want to understate the importance of the
area for birds in winter.'
The oil spill from the wreck of the Aegean Sea off the north-west coast of
Spain just before Christmas killed about 3,000 seabirds, but that area is
not noted for its bird populations. 'My feeling is if we come out that lucky
we will be very, very happy,' Ms Harrison said. 'I think it will be more
than that.'
The birds most immediately under threat in the Shetlands are sea duck and
diving species. The Wildfowl and Wetlands Trust rates Shetland as probably
Britain's most important site for wintering sea ducks, with about 10,300
wintering birds - roughly 7 per cent of the UK population.
Shetland has colonies of eider, long-tailed duck and large numbers of
guillemots and shag. Other seabirds such as the fulmar, little auk and great
northern diver are also vulnerable. Dr Harrison said the threat to colonies
of black guillemot was particularly worrying because local populations would
be unlikely to recover quickly.
Some colonies have still not recovered from the last big spill in the area
in 1979, when the tanker Esso Bernicia ran into a terminal at Sullom Voe.
About 3,700 birds died and the eider duck population declined by more than a
quarter between 1979 and 1984.
Mr Ian McCall, conservation officer at the RSPB's Scottish office, said the
tanker could not have run aground at a more sensitive spot: Shetland was one
of the most important wildlife centres in the whole north-east Atlantic
region.
Wildlife conservationists were hoping last night that coast-dwelling species
in the Sumburgh area would have been on the opposite side of the headland,
sheltering from the storm. Tens of thousands of other seabirds that nest
among Shetland's cliff colonies are well out at sea, where they feed and
live after the breeding season, returning in the spring.
There are fears that if much oil leaks into the sea it might circulate
around the islands, making a rapid clean-up difficult. In such
circumstances, it would be a struggle to have the shores cleaned before the
sea-ranging birds return to nest in a few months.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
THE BRAER: ROUTE TO DISASTER
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
THE COUNTDOWN
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
05:30  Braer engines fail.
07:20  Tug Start Sirius despatched from Lerwick Harbour, 30 miles away.
       Sullom Voe tug Swaabie also en route. Lerwick lifeboat and
       Coastguard Rescue helicopter at scene.
08:45  Tanker only one mile off rocks at Horse Island, Sumburgh Head.
09:00  RAF rescue helicopter from Lossiemouth lifted off last of the
       34 man crew.
10:55  Tanker taken in tow by Star Sirius and Swaabie in attempt to
       pull clear.
11:15  Tanker aground on Fitful Head. Oil already leaking. Shetland
       Islands Council activated major disaster plan to try to limit
       environmental damage.
11:25  Shetland Coastguards confirm Braer aground on rocks at Garths
       Ness on southern tip of Shetland Islands.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
THE VOYAGE
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
The Braer left Mongstad near Bergen in Norway on Sunday heading for
   Quebec in Canada.
Chartered course through the middle of the notoriously choppy
   22-mile-wide channel between Sumburgh Head and Fair Isle. It kept 10
   miles away from the coast in line with advice from maritime
   authorities.
Seas are usually calmer taking route around Herma Ness, but that adds
   60 miles to journey.
In the early hours of yesterday morning, in a force 10 storm, engine
   problems caused the tanker to begin drifting. It ran aground at
   Garths Ness near Sumburgh Head.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
ENDANGERED WILDLIFE
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Great northern divers
Eider duck
Black guillemot
Other birds which nest on Shetland are currently at sea and will not
return till the spring. They include:
Gannet
Guillemot
Razorbill
Puffin
Other animals under threat include otters, seals, porpoises and whales
