FT  06 JAN 93 / Bush hoping for trade pact
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
American trade officials yesterday were said to be mulling over potential US
concessions designed to achieve the breakthrough needed if the Uruguay Round
of trade liberalisation talks is to conclude during the tenure of President
George Bush, writes Nancy Dunne in Washington.
Mr Bush, apparently determined to 'leave the desk clean' when he turns over
the presidency to Governor Bill Clinton on January 20, has been pushing to
meet the January 15 deadline he last month set with British Prime Minister
John Major for final resolution of the most important issues.
After signing the Start 2 nuclear arms accord in Russia at the weekend, the
president stopped off in Paris to discuss the General Agreement on Tariffs
and Trade with French President Francois Mitterrand. Reportedly, he made
little headway.
At the same time, Mrs Carla Hills, the US trade representative, met Sir Leon
Brittan, newly appointed as EC Commissioner for External Relations and Trade
to discuss 'a shopping list' of issues.
